Recurrent Neural Networks and Stock Price Prediciton Project (Exam 3)

Exam includes: Fetched stocks from Yahoo Finance, XGBoost classifier, Time series split, CNN, MLP, GRU, GeLU (has a greater advantage for stocks than ReLU based activation functions), ReLU, sigmoid, softmax, and tanh activations, categorical_crossentropy, and additional insight into accuracy and RMSE via log bar graphs. Results are performances of models with their trained and validation parameters to show which model is best and worst at handling these combinations of stocks (Apple, Dollar General, Blackberry, Amazon, and S&P 500 ETF). Deals with combination of stocks instead of each stock individually for generalized performances, less extraneous work, and identifying common patterns/shifts within these stocks including their feature column labels along with target outside of the column labels. Each model is over 50 epochs without early stopping to visualize a greater outlook of the performances over each epoch.

import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
import yfinance as yf
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.model_selection import train_test_split
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
from xgboost import XGBClassifier
from sklearn.metrics import classification_report, accuracy_score, mean_squared_error
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
from sklearn.metrics import ConfusionMatrixDisplay

# 3) My Own Implementation

# WILL FOCUS ON: CNN, MLP, GRU, LSTM, XGBoost, ReLU activations, Time Series Split

# BUILD XGBoost MODEL FIRST

# Fetch the stocks I want
stocks_dict = {
    "Apple": "AAPL",
    "Dollar General": "DG",
    "Blackberry": "BB",
    "Amazon": "AMZN",
    "S&P 500 ETF": "SPY"
}

# Hold the data for the stocks
stocks_data = {}

# Instantiate the features in the columns (exlcuding Target)
feature_cols = ['Return', 'Volume_Change', 'MA_Ratio1', 'MA_Ratio2', 'Volatility',
                'Return_Prev1', 'Return_Prev2', 'Volume_Change_Prev1']
# Combine all data for a generalized outlook of the stocks
combined_data = []

# Download all of the stocks
for name, ticker in stocks_dict.items():
  df = yf.download(ticker, start="2010-01-01", end="2023-11-13")[['Close', 'Volume']].dropna().reset_index()
  # Standard features via YF
  df['Return'] = df['Close'].pct_change()
  df['Volume_Change'] = df['Volume'].pct_change()

  # Additional features that can help with improving scores
  # Also, with outlook of stocks
  # MA = Moving Averages
  df['MA5'] = df['Close'].rolling(window=5).mean()
  df['MA20'] = df['Close'].rolling(window=20).mean()
  df['MA100'] = df['Close'].rolling(window=100).mean()
  # Follows trend of stocks
  df['MA_Ratio1'] = df['MA5'] / df['MA20']
  df['MA_Ratio2'] = df['MA20'] / df['MA100']
  df['Volatility'] = df['Return'].rolling(window=20).std()

  # Lag features
  # Used to predict future values
  df['Return_Prev1'] = df['Return'].shift(1)
  df['Return_Prev2'] = df['Return'].shift(2)
  df['Volume_Change_Prev1'] = df['Volume_Change'].shift(1)

  # Creating conditions and corresponding values
  # Allows to greater analyze the return and improve outlook of model
  conditions = [
      # 0.005 works best universally here
      df['Return'].shift(-1) < -0.005,
      (df['Return'].shift(-1) >= -0.005) & (df['Return'].shift(-1) <= 0.005),
      df['Return'].shift(-1) > 0.005
  ]
  # Three classes with 0 index
  values = [0, 1, 2]

  # Assign target to the three clases via an array
  df['Target'] = np.select(conditions, values, default=np.nan)
  df = df.dropna()
  combined_data.append(df)

combined_df = pd.concat(combined_data, ignore_index=True)

X = combined_df[feature_cols]
y = combined_df['Target']

# Time split
train_size = int(len(X) * 0.75)
X_train = X.iloc[:train_size]
X_test = X.iloc[train_size:]
y_train = y.iloc[:train_size]
y_test = y.iloc[train_size:]

# Build Pipeline: Scale + XGBoost
pipeline = Pipeline([
    ('scale', StandardScaler()),
    ('xgb', XGBClassifier(
        # These are the best possible metrics
        # For the best outlook of the model
        # Including the confusion matrix
        n_estimators=200,
        max_depth=6,
        learning_rate=0.1,
        subsample=0.8,
        colsample_bytree=0.8,
        min_child_weight=1,
        use_label_encoder=False,
        eval_metric='mlogloss',
        objective='multi:softprob'
    ))
])

# Train & predict
pipeline.fit(X_train, y_train)
y_pred = pipeline.predict(X_test)

print(classification_report(y_test, y_pred))

# RMSE
xgb_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test, y_pred))
print(f"RMSE: {xgb_rmse:.2f}")

# Now how well does the model perform with the combined stocks?
ConfusionMatrixDisplay.from_predictions(y_test, y_pred)
plt.title(f"Combined Stocks - Confusion Matrix")
plt.show()

# Create the sequences for the train and test values
def create_sequences(data, timesteps):
  X = []
  y = []
  for i in range(len(data) - timesteps):
    X.append(data[i:i + timesteps])
    y.append(data[i + timesteps])
  return np.array(X), np.array(y)

# 25 works best here
timesteps = 25

# Sequences for training data
X_train_cnn, y_train_cnn = create_sequences(X_train.values, timesteps)
y_train_cnn = y_train.values[timesteps:]

# Sequences for testing data
X_test_cnn, y_test_cnn = create_sequences(X_test.values, timesteps)
y_test_cnn = y_test.values[timesteps:]

from tensorflow.keras.models import Sequential
from tensorflow.keras.layers import Conv1D, GlobalMaxPooling1D, Dense, Dropout, Input
from tensorflow.keras.callbacks import EarlyStopping

# 1D CNN Layers

# CNN
# With 1D conversion, relu, and dropout
cnn = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(timesteps, X_train.shape[1])),
    # Gelu is better for stocks than Relu
    Conv1D(filters=16, kernel_size=2, activation='gelu'),
    GlobalMaxPooling1D(),
    # Tanh is appropriate here rather than sigmoid
    Dense(32, activation='tanh'),
    Dropout(0.15),
    Dense(3, activation='softmax')
])

# Compile
cnn.compile(
    optimizer='adam',
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

# Train model
cnn_history = cnn.fit(X_train_cnn, y_train_cnn, batch_size=32, epochs=50,
                  validation_split=0.2)

# Make predictions
cnn_predictions = cnn.predict(X_test_cnn)
cnn_pred_classes = np.argmax(cnn_predictions, axis=1)
y_test_classes = np.argmax(y_test_cnn, axis=1)

# Evaluate model
cnn.evaluate(X_test_cnn, y_test_cnn)
print("CNN Model Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test_classes, cnn_pred_classes))
print(classification_report(y_test_classes, cnn_pred_classes))

# RMSE
cnn_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_classes, cnn_pred_classes))
print(f"CNN RMSE: {cnn_rmse:.2f}")

    Input(shape=(timesteps, X_train.shape[1])),
    Flatten(),
    Dense(25, activation='gelu'),
    Dropout(0.15),

# LSTM Model
from tensorflow.keras.layers import LSTM
from tensorflow.keras.optimizers import Adam

lstm = Sequential([
    Input(shape=(timesteps, X_train.shape[1])),
    LSTM(100, return_sequences=False),
    Dense(25, activation='gelu'),
    Dense(3, activation='softmax')
])

lstm.compile(
    optimizer=Adam(learning_rate=0.001),
    loss='categorical_crossentropy',
    metrics=['accuracy']
)

lstm_history = lstm.fit(X_train_cnn, y_train_cnn, batch_size=32, epochs=50,
                        validation_split=0.2)

# Make the predictions
lstm_predictions = lstm.predict(X_test_cnn)
lstm_pred_classes = np.argmax(lstm_predictions, axis=1)

# One-hot encoded y_test -> class indices
y_test_classes = (np.argmax(y_test_cnn, axis=1)
                  if len(y_test_cnn.shape) > 1 and y_test_cnn.shape[1] > 1
                  else y_test_cnn)

# Evaluate model
print("LSTM Model Accuracy:", accuracy_score(y_test_classes, lstm_pred_classes))
print(classification_report(y_test_classes, lstm_pred_classes))

# RMSE
lstm_rmse = np.sqrt(mean_squared_error(y_test_classes, lstm_pred_classes))
print(f"LSTM RMSE: {lstm_rmse:.2f}")

# Visualize the performance of the training and validation sets per iteration
def plot_history(history, label):
  plt.plot(history.history['accuracy'], label=f'{label} Train')
  plt.plot(history.history['val_accuracy'], label=f'{label} Val')
  plt.xlabel('Epoch')
  plt.ylabel('Accuracy')
  plt.legend()
  plt.title(f'Model Accuracy - {label}')
  plt.grid(True)

plt.figure(figsize=(12, 8))
plot_history(cnn_history, "CNN")
plot_history(mlp_history, "MLP")
plot_history(lstm_history, "LSTM")
plot_history(gru_history, "GRU")
plt.title("Training and Validation Accuracy for CNN, MLP, LSTM, and GRU Models")
plt.legend()
plt.grid(True)

Examples
--------

    The simplest way to use nbconvert is

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to html

            Options include ['asciidoc', 'custom', 'html', 'latex', 'markdown', 'notebook', 'pdf', 'python', 'qtpdf', 'qtpng', 'rst', 'script', 'slides', 'webpdf'].

            > jupyter nbconvert --to latex mynotebook.ipynb

            Both HTML and LaTeX support multiple output templates. LaTeX includes
            'base', 'article' and 'report'.  HTML includes 'basic', 'lab' and
            'classic'. You can specify the flavor of the format used.

            > jupyter nbconvert --to html --template lab mynotebook.ipynb

            You can also pipe the output to stdout, rather than a file

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --stdout

            PDF is generated via latex

            > jupyter nbconvert mynotebook.ipynb --to pdf

            You can get (and serve) a Reveal.js-powered slideshow

            > jupyter nbconvert myslides.ipynb --to slides --post serve

            Multiple notebooks can be given at the command line in a couple of
            different ways:

            > jupyter nbconvert notebook*.ipynb
            > jupyter nbconvert notebook1.ipynb notebook2.ipynb

            or you can specify the notebooks list in a config file, containing::

                c.NbConvertApp.notebooks = ["my_notebook.ipynb"]

            > jupyter nbconvert --config mycfg.py

To see all available configurables, use `--help-all`.
